data("BCI")

BCI_xy = data.frame(x = rep(seq(625754, 626654, by=100), each=5), 
                    y = rep(seq(1011569,  1011969, by=100), len=50))
species_abundance = colSums(BCI)

hist(log10(species_abundance))

ifelse(species_abundance > 1000, print(BCI[,]), NA)
ifelse(species_abundance > 10 & species_abundance < 20, print(BCI[,]), NA)
common = BCI$Trichilia.tuberculata

rare = BCI$Siparuna.guianensis

common2 = BCI$Faramea.occidentalis

rare2 = BCI$Cavanillesia.platanifolia
hist(common)

col_brks = hist(common, plot = F)$breaks
col_indices = as.numeric(cut(common, col_brks))
cols = rev(terrain.colors(length(col_brks)))
plot(BCI_xy, pch = 19, cex = 2, col=cols[col_indices])

hist(common2)

col_brks_2 = hist(common2, plot = F)$breaks
col_indices_2 = as.numeric(cut(common2, col_brks))
cols_2 = rev(terrain.colors(length(col_brks)))
plot(BCI_xy, pch = 19, cex = 2, col=cols[col_indices_2])

The above two plots are plots of the abundance of the two most common species in the data. The first plot shows very little to no spatial dependence because the scarce sites (brown sites) are scattered throughout the plot with no pattern and the two green dots are surrounded by both brown and pink sites (no yellow sites) showing that there is no pattern to the abundance around those sites. The second plot shows more of a trend, indicating more spatial dependence, but still not a lot. The trend starts on the left and the abundance increases until it reaches the green dot (most abundant) and then drops off to barely anything after that. While this trend is apparent, brown, yellow, white and pink dots are still scattered throughout the sites, showing randomization within the trend.

col_brks_rare = hist(rare, plot = F)$breaks
col_indices_rare = as.numeric(cut(rare, col_brks_rare))
cols_rare = rev(terrain.colors(length(col_brks_rare)))
plot(BCI_xy, pch = 19, cex = 2, col=cols[col_indices_rare])

col_brks_rare2 = hist(rare2, plot = F)$breaks
col_indices_rare2 = as.numeric(cut(rare2, col_brks_rare2))
cols_rare2 = rev(terrain.colors(length(col_brks_rare2)))
plot(BCI_xy, pch = 19, cex = 2, col=cols[col_indices_rare2])

These two plots above are of two rare species of tree. Rare in this case is between 10 and 20 occurences. I needed a species that would have enough to show if there was any spatial dependence but that was still scarce enough to be considered rare. The first plot shows more spatial dependence than the second, with there being a central high abundancy point and a decrease spreading from that one site. The second plot seems more random because of the lack of data to the left of all the dots and then the one yellow and one orange dot, showing no trend. After analyzing all four of these plots, I can come to the conclusion that while there may be very little spatial dependency within the data, it is not a lot, and we will go on to see if it is enough to have to male up for it in the model.

gls_all_predictors = gls(Drypetes.standleyi ~ Cordia.lasiocalyx + Hirtella.triandra + Picramnia.latifolia + Quassia.amara +
           Tabernaemontana.arborea + Trattinnickia.aspera +  Xylopia.macrantha, data = BCI)

gls_one_predictor = gls(Drypetes.standleyi ~ Quassia.amara, data = BCI)
gls_one_predictor
## Generalized least squares fit by REML
##   Model: Drypetes.standleyi ~ Quassia.amara 
##   Data: BCI

## 
## Coefficients:

##      4.962810      9.214876 
## 
## Degrees of freedom: 50 total; 48 residual
## Residual standard error: 7.171316
x <- BCI_xy$x
y <- BCI_xy$y
one_predictor_exp = update(gls_one_predictor, corr=corExp(form = ~ x + y))

plot(Variogram(one_predictor_exp))

plot(Variogram(one_predictor_exp, resType='normalized'))

The model does seem to fit the error well and the residuals do not have a pattern (they are scattered around the line). These show that the model fits the data and there may not be a nugget needed. This was proved when Iattempted to include the nugget and it threw an error about there being a “false convergence (8).” I read online that this has something to do with the nugget’s influence being too small so it throws an error. This further proved that there is little spatial dependence in this data.

gls_all_predictors_exp = update(gls_all_predictors, corr=corExp(form = ~ x + y))

plot(Variogram(gls_all_predictors_exp))

plot(Variogram(one_predictor_exp, resType='normalized'))

These plots produce a similar answer to the previous plots. The error is predicted well by the model and the residuals are not in a pattern, indicating that they are normally distributed. Even though when looking at the Variogram it does not look like a nugget is needed, I attempted to include one and the same error was thrown.

Adding the error term had a huge impact on the coefficients of the model; it made the models worse. The F-Values were much higher and the p-values were much lower before altering it with the exponential correlation. This is due to the fact that there is little spatial dependence in the data but we accounted for it with the exponential error structure.
